Coffee Retreats Amid European Debt Crisis

-- B y   I s i s   A l m e i d a
-- 
2011-07-12T11:48:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-12/coffee-retreats-amid-european-debt-crisis.html
Coffee fell for a third day in  New
York , reaching the lowest level this month, as concerns  Europe ’s
sovereign debt woes will worsen helped lift the U.S. dollar.
Soft commodities such as sugar and cocoa also slid.  European finance ministers revived the prospect of bond
buybacks to ease  Greece ’s plight and declined to rule out a
temporary default as they struggled to contain the debt crisis
that has now affected  Italy . The U.S. Dollar Index climbed as
much as 1 percent, while the Standard and Poor’s GSCI spot index
of raw materials declined as much as 1.4 percent.  “With the fears of default on debt and new potential
bailouts now surrounding Italy and possibly  Spain , the markets
have been affected by sudden strength in the  U.S. dollar ,”
Sucden Financial analyst Nick Penney wrote in a report today. A
stronger dollar makes commodities priced in the currency more
expensive in terms of other monies.  Arabica coffee for September delivery retreated 3.70 cents,
or 1.4 percent, to $2.5535 a pound by 7:13 a.m. on ICE Futures
U.S. in New York, the lowest price this month. Robusta coffee
for September delivery slid $87, or 3.7 percent, to $2,267 a
metric ton on NYSE Liffe in London.  The risk that commodity prices will suffer a deflationary
decline is rising, Luis Rangel, vice president of commodity
derivatives at ICAP Futures LLC, wrote in a report yesterday.  Crystal Sugar  Raw sugar for October slid 0.27 cent, or 0.9 percent, to
28.65 cents a pound on ICE. White, or refined, sugar for October
delivery retreated $4.80, or 0.6 percent, to $742 a ton on NYSE
Liffe.  The price of crystal sugar in  Brazil , the world’s largest
producer, climbed 7.3 percent in the first week of this month as
strong demand continues to drive prices, according to Cepea, a
University of Sao Paulo research group. The variety accounts for
68 percent of the sweetener sold within Brazil.  Industry group Unica will revise its estimate of Brazil’s
Center South 2011-12 crop tomorrow, it said in an e-mail
yesterday. Rabobank International lowered its projection for the
cane crop in the area, Brazil’s main producing region, to 540
million tons from 569 million tons, analyst Keith Flury said in
an e-mail response to questions today.  Cocoa for September delivery declined $27, or 0.9 percent,
to $3,023 a ton in New York. Cocoa for September delivery fell 6
pounds, or 0.3 percent, to 1,927 pounds ($3,049) a ton in
 London .  To contact the reporter on this story:
